timetraveller (1.4.1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fix: deleting a system-class plan's archives (system/homes) from the GUI did
    nothing -- the worker ran as the unprivileged GUI user and hit a
    PermissionError on the root-owned archive files (crashing with a raw
    traceback). Delete now escalates via a new pkexec helper
    (timetraveller-delete-system-archives + com.timetraveller.delete-system-
    archives.policy), mirroring how save/schedule already escalate. The helper
    validates the plan allowlist, the action, and a strict identifier charset
    (no path traversal / arg smuggling), then re-execs the canonical binary
    against the root-owned /etc config so deletion stays contained. After a
    privileged delete the invoking user's local manifest mirror is resynced
    from the mount so the GUI reflects the change without a manual refresh.
    --force is forwarded only when the caller passed it, preserving the
    newest-complete-cycle guard. A residual PermissionError now prints a clean,
    actionable message instead of a traceback.
  * Packaging: prerm now strips TimeTraveller's managed cron blocks from root's
    crontab (system/homes plans) and any user crontab (user plans) on
    `apt remove`, so uninstalling no longer leaves cron entries that invoke a
    deleted binary. Best-effort: a cron hiccup never blocks package removal.

