timetraveller (1.4.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Archive integrity: per-frame SHA-256, computed inline as each 64 MiB zstd
    frame is written (no extra pass -- the bytes are already in hand), recorded
    in the frames.json sidecar (now version 2, csum_algo "sha256"). The frame
    compressor also enables zstd's own per-frame content checksum, so every
    decompression (restore/browse/recover) self-verifies automatically. Catches
    corruption introduced anywhere from compression onward (write buffer, NFS,
    network, storage) -- a real 8-of-4273-frame corruption on a 2026-06-14 full
    motivated this. See docs/design/archive-integrity.md (incl. the non-ECC RAM
    limitation, deliberately out of scope).
  * --verify reworked: checks integrity by re-reading each frame and comparing
    its SHA-256 -- no decompression -- and reports the exact corrupt frames. Now
    shard-group aware (verify a whole logical backup by its stem) and includes
    quarantined .failed archives. v1 archives fall back to a full decompress.
  * Fix false "failed" classification: a "file changed as we read it" warning
    (a benign exit-1 race, e.g. an idle browser's automatic cache cleanup
    rewriting files mid-read) co-occurring with a vanished-file line on the
    exit-2 path was wrongly tipping the whole run to failed. Such lines are now
    recognised as benign, matching the vanished-file (ENOENT) handling.

 -- Kim McCann <amplogik@gmail.com>  Sun, 14 Jun 2026 09:30:00 -0700

timetraveller (1.3.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Self-describing archives: each shard now gets a <archive>.meta.json sidecar
    (one serialized manifest entry, incl. the shard fields). It is written on
    backup from the in-memory entry -- NO extra read of the archive, so the
    single-read write path from the inline-index work is preserved. --reindex
    backfills it for older archives.
  * Manifest rebuild from a bare directory: --list-archives --refresh-from-mount
    now reconstructs a lost/absent on-mount manifest.json from the .meta.json
    sidecars (grouping shards back into sets), so a hand-moved or partially-
    restored archive directory becomes browsable again.
  * Export bundle: --export-cycle CYCLE_ID / --export-set GROUP_ID --into DIR
    copy a whole logical backup (every shard + .idx.zst/.frames.json/.meta.json
    sidecars + a self-contained manifest slice) as one group-atomic set, and
    refuse to write a partial bundle if a shard is missing on the mount. GUI:
    "Export cycle…" / "Export backup…" in the Archives right-click menu (pick a
    target directory; non-destructive, so no type-to-confirm).

