timetraveller (1.1.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Sharding: a backup can now be written as N parallel pax|zstd streams to N
    shard archives instead of one, using the otherwise-idle CPU cores. The
    single-thread tar producer (not compression, not the 10GbE link) was the
    write bottleneck; parallel shards raise throughput toward the storage
    backend's ceiling. Because it optimises the client, the win is
    backend-agnostic (NFS, SMB, S3, any target) — no server-side tuning needed.
  * New per-plan `shards` setting: "auto" (default; min(cores-2, 4)) or an
    integer. The count is capped at runtime by the backup's size (~1 GiB per
    shard) and file count, so small backups and most incrementals stay
    single-stream. `shards: 1` keeps the historical single-archive behaviour.
  * One backup = one logical "shard set". The N shards share a shard_group and
    are surfaced as a single backup to cycles and retention (a sharded full
    counts as one cycle; all its shards are pruned together). Manifest schema
    bumped to v2 (shard_index/shard_count/shard_group); v1 manifests load and
    upgrade transparently.
  * Restore is shard-aware: `--extract` accepts a shard-set stem (e.g.
    2026-06-13_full), a shard filename, or a plain archive name and gathers the
    requested files from whichever shards hold them. Each shard keeps its own
    inline .idx.zst / .frames.json, so per-file fast-extract is unchanged.
  * GUI lists every shard of a sharded backup (none hidden) and includes them
    all in file search. (Collapsing a shard set into a single row with a merged
    file tree is a planned follow-up.)

 -- Kim McCann <amplogik@gmail.com>  Sat, 13 Jun 2026 10:49:17 -0700

timetraveller (1.0.7) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Inline index build: framed backups now build the .idx.zst sidecar
    during the archive write instead of in a second pass that re-read and
    re-decompressed the whole archive afterward. On the NFS target that
    second pass was ~23% of wall time (~28 min on the 753 GiB home full,
    bound by the NFS read of the just-written archive); folding it into
    the write eliminates that read entirely. A background InlineIndexWriter
    is fed the uncompressed tar stream the framewriter already consumes and
    emits the identical v2 JSONL records, so the on-disk format and all
    sidecar/extract readers are unchanged (validated byte-identical to the
    post-write build, including long-name/symlink/hardlink entries, and
    against a real fast single-file extract).
  * Fallbacks preserved: --no-framed keeps the post-write index pass, any
    inline-build failure degrades to that same pass rather than failing the
    backup, and --reindex remains the repair path for old or missing
    sidecars. The backup's worst case is unchanged; the common framed path
    drops the second archive read.

 -- Kim McCann <amplogik@gmail.com>  Sat, 13 Jun 2026 06:38:36 -0700

timetraveller (1.0.6) unstable; urgency=medium

  * New --recover-failed action: un-quarantine a backup marked 'failed'
    whose archive stream is actually intact. A failed run renames its
    archive to <name>.failed on disk while the manifest keeps the bare
    name; some failures (most commonly a file vanishing mid-walk -> tar
    exit 2, the same benign race v1.0.5 now tolerates for new runs) leave
    a structurally valid stream, others (truncation, zstd corruption) do
    not. The action renames <name>.failed back, builds the .idx.zst
    sidecar straight off the archive -- which streams the whole thing
    through tarfile and so doubles as the integrity gate -- and finalizes
    the manifest entry to 'ok-with-warnings'. If the stream is truncated
    or corrupt the archive is re-quarantined to .failed and the entry
    stays 'failed', so the manifest<->disk invariant holds for a retry.
  * GUI: failed archives now offer a Recover button on the Archives panel
    instead of the previous "backup failed; archive incomplete" dead-end.
    It launches --recover-failed as a detached, restart-surviving job
    (same machinery as the v1.0.4 Reindex button, now generalized to
    arbitrary worker jobs under per-action state subdirs); on success the
    listing refreshes and the file tree loads, on failure a modal shows
    the log tail and re-offers the button for retry.
  * index.write_sidecar no longer leaves a partial <name>.idx.zst.tmp
    behind when the archive stream raises mid-read (surfaced by running
    the sidecar build as a recovery integrity gate); the temp file is
    removed before the error propagates.

 -- Kim McCann <amplogik@gmail.com>  Sat, 13 Jun 2026 06:25:23 -0700

timetraveller (1.0.5) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Backup: a file vanishing mid-walk no longer fails the whole run.
    The backup enumerates the file list first, then streams those paths
    to GNU tar; volatile trees (browser caches, Brave's "Safe Browsing/
    *.store") rotate constantly, so a listed file can be gone before tar
    stats it. tar reports "Cannot stat: No such file or directory" and
    exits 2 — but it skips the missing member and the archive stream
    stays structurally valid, exactly the same benign race as the exit-1
    "file changed as we read it" case. RunResult.status now downgrades a
    tar exit >=2 to "ok-with-warnings" when every diagnostic is such a
    per-file ENOENT (or the generic failure-summary trailer); the run
    keeps its inline sidecar/frame index and is no longer quarantined to
    a `.failed` file. Any other fatal line (ENOSPC, permission denied), a
    zstd failure, or stderr we could not capture still fails the run.
  * Internal: pax stderr is now captured (teed to the run log and kept,
    bounded to 1 MiB, on RunResult.pax_stderr) via a reader thread in
    pax.run/run_with_file_list so status classification can inspect it.

 -- Kim McCann <amplogik@gmail.com>  Sat, 13 Jun 2026 06:02:39 -0700

timetraveller (1.0.4) unstable; urgency=medium

  * GUI: Reindex button on the Archives panel for archives that are
    missing their .idx.zst sidecar. Launches the worker as a detached
    process (its own session group) so the long-running reindex
    survives a GUI exit. The label changes to "Indexing now" while a
    reindex is in flight, restored to the idle warning on completion
    (success refreshes the archive listing and re-selects the archive;
    failure pops a modal with the log tail and re-offers the button
    for retry). Per-(plan, archive) pid/log/done state files under
    XDG_STATE_HOME let a fresh GUI session adopt a still-running
    reindex launched by a prior session. Failed archives (status =
    "failed") are explicitly carved out — the archive file is at
    `.failed` suffix on disk and the worker's --reindex would not
    find it; those entries show "backup failed; archive incomplete"
    with no button.
  * GUI: cross-archive file search in the Archives panel. A new
    "Search files…" button toggles the right pane from the per-archive
    file tree to a grouped search-results view. Each matching file
    path becomes a top-level row; under it, one row per archive that
    contains a copy, with size and mtime-at-backup so the user can
    pick the right version to restore. Streaming sidecar scan with a
    bytes-level case-folded substring prefilter keeps the search
    sub-second per million-entry sidecar; results are off-thread in a
    QThread worker. Min 3 chars, capped at 500 distinct paths.
    Activating a version row exits search, selects the archive on the
    left, and scrolls the file tree to the path so Extract is one
    click away.

